What you get when you work with me: hand drawn, custom branding, packaging, and illustration. ✨ Of course, this is only what you see. There’s so much that goes into being a business owner and creator: 5 years of school, programs (I use about 10 right now to run my biz), iPad, desktop, computer, hard drives, legal fees, taxes, and a lot of other surprising expenses that pop up along the way. Don’t get me wrong - I would not trade my job for anything. I really love what I do so so much. Most of the time it doesn’t feel like a job. But when you inquire with an artist, designer or illustrator, just keep in mind all that goes into it, who you’re working with, and the passion and love it takes to create something impactful.✨ 
.

“Where do I start?” - a question I hear a lot from aspiring freelancers. My answer: just start! The longer you keep asking yourself that question, the more time you aren’t taking advantage of. It might take awhile for you to be confident in your abilities, but the more you practice and push yourself to try new things, the faster you will get to where you want to be. 

I’m going on my 7th year as a freelancer, and I still get stuck in circles in my head with thoughts like “I’ve never done this before, and I know I can do it but I’m still doubting myself.” There are always going to be new horizons that you have to tackle. And you might surprise yourself with what you are capable of. So stop doubting yourself. Stop avoiding the start line, and just go for it! People don’t know what you’re capable of, and you don’t know either - until you start. 💫

If you’re stuck, I’m here to talk! DM me and let’s schedule a guidance call to push past your creative blocks. It’s your time to make big moves.💫

Hey there! It’s been awhile since I introduced myself. First off, thank you for following my account and being a part of my creative freelance journey! I’m Ashley - an artist, designer and illustrator based in North County San Diego. This account showcases a lot of my personal illustration, which I have a big passion for. But if you didn’t know, I also run my own design studio called Libra Collective where I get to design and illustrate for clients all of the world! Our projects range from brand identity to packaging and custom illustrations used in a variety of ways. I absolutely love working with clients that are passionate about what they do, and who look to me to bring their ideas from thought to form. 💫 I also love talking with new creatives that are interested in turning their talents into a business like I have! I offer guidance calls and Adobe program tutorials for aspiring freelancers so they can gain confidence to make their own stars align with their skills! Long story short - I love creating for people, helping others learn, and watching them grow as I have done in my own business. Thanks for being here and supporting my creations! Here’s to stars aligning through creativity!💫

To learn more about Libra Co. design services and guidance for creatives, visit: Libracollective.com 

*link is also in my bio ☀️😉

Let’s talk about ORGANIZATION✨✔️
Organization is something I cannot live without. With how many clients I have had over the years it’s so important for me to be able to find things easily. 

Folders vary from project to project, but these are the main ones that I create right away when I onboard a new client:

•CLIENT INFO
•INSPO
•STOCK PHOTOS
•MOCK-UPS
•WORKING FILES
•FINAL FILES

There are always folders within these folders, but these are the “first layer”.📁 What other folders help keep you organized?

#design #organization #fileorganization #graphicdesign #designtips #illustration #adobe #illustration #illustrator

There comes a time in a creative’s life when we must decide what we want to do for the rest of our careers.

I was born and raised an artist - from the moment I could pick up a Crayola. Growing up, I tried every medium and loved painting especially. After high school, I attended community college to take art classes - oil painting, life drawing, and ceramics. But I didn’t have a goal in mind for my future career. When the time came for me to decide, I chose to pursue a degree in graphic design at Laguna College of Art and Design. Thanks to my 6th grade Intro to Photoshop class, I had an interest in creating things on the computer and felt that graphic design would be a sustainable career choice. Other than that, I had no knowledge about graphic design. 8 years later, here I am. 

In college I started telling people I was a graphic designer, even though I had a lot to learn, but it led to some jobs. That snowballed, and I never stopped putting myself out there. Freelance has given me the power to create the life I want to live, and has allowed me to work with so many people all over the world! It’s hard work, but I wouldn’t trade it for anything. 

If you’re a fine artist, graphic designer, illustrator, photographer, videographer - or any type of creative…. don’t think that you can’t explore other mediums and paths for your creative career. That’s the beauty of being a creative person! We have a lot to share with the world. Show people what you are capable of, in all forms!

I get overly excited when my clients want to incorporate illustrations into their projects! Most of the time when I tell people I’m a designer and illustrator, they don’t fully understand how the two work together. They are different forms of art, but work beautifully together in so many ways! 

Graphic design is a combination of typography, grids, color codes, photos, layouts, etc. and illustration is more related to fine art, as a visual interpretation of a thought, feeling, or idea. 

Here I share a few project examples of things I have designed/illustrated over the years for my clients.

•logo design
•apparel graphics 
•book illustrations (covers and interior)
•social and web icons
•custom merchandise
•brochure covers (they don’t have to be boring!)
•GIFs (animated illustrations)
•packaging

Let’s talk about the PROS and CONS of freelancing! These are from my experience of being a freelancer for 7 years, and the cons are really just part of learning and have made be a better business woman. What other ones would you add to this list?

PROS:
•You get to make your own schedule
• Variation in projects, depending on your skillset
• Working with clients from all over
• Being in charge (if you value a leadership position)
• Sleeping in
• Taking time off when you want to
• No commuting
• Working at coffee shops, or home in your PJs
• Have more time to work out, cook at home, slow down

CONS:
• Being in charge of your expenses, taxes, and bookkeeping (if you don’t hire someone)
• No insurance or 401k benefits
• Handling some difficult client relationships
• Making sure you get paid on time
• Contracts and other legal stuff
• Marketing yourself properly
• Making sure you are ahead of your competitors
• Working solo most of the time
.
.
.
.
.

For the past few years, I have been using a notebook as a planner, and writing in my dates, because I didn’t like committing to a planner and all of the fluff that are usually in them. It’s too overwhelming for me, so I decided to create a simple planner, allowing me to fill in dates, reminders, and my to-do list. 

8 of these planners will be available for purchase on Tuesday, January 2nd, 2024, at 11am PST at libracollective.com/shop! (U.S. only)

Here are some of the features:
• I didn’t like committing to a planner with set dates, so I created one where I could write in my own dates.
• Adding in my mindset for the week, and weekly reflection adds intention and mindfulness without being overbearing.
• I wanted to have a “reminders” section for important meetings so they didn’t get lost in my to-do list for the day.
• I also wanted simplicity in the design so I didn’t feel obligated to fill out certain sections that I would never use.
• I used to cross out my to-do items, but how cute is it to just have a little circle so you can check off your items instead?!
• And most importantly I wanted the cover to pop! A simple, but groovy and colorful design was the goal. 🪩

Here’s a snapshot of my personal brand “Ashley Munson”🌼 I am a groovy 60s/70s/disco/flower lover at heart, so that was the inspiration for the logo, color and type. My personal brand is aligned with who and what I want to be working on, moving forward in my freelance career.

When creating a personal brand for yourself, it’s important to take time to recognize the bigger picture for yourself as a creative. Ask questions like:
• What kind of clients and projects do I want to be working on? 
• What creatively lights me up inside? 
• What style am I drawn to? 

The answers to these questions help guide your creative development and will drive your personal style as a designer, artist, photographer, painter, etc. 

The more you pay attention to your inner compass of where you want to go, the more your work will reflect that. Sometimes we just have to listen to ourselves more than anything to get there. Trends fade. Your uniqueness will always be. 🌼🪩✨
